// Program B: an AWS Lambda function written in ai-lang, running as a
// custom runtime. The whole thing is ai-lang — including the runtime
// loop that speaks the Lambda Runtime API over HTTP.
//
// `lambda_serve` (stdlib) reads AWS_LAMBDA_RUNTIME_API from the
// environment (AWS sets it), then loops forever: GET the next invocation
// (reading its request id from a response header), run `handler` on the
// event body, and POST the result back to the per-invocation endpoint.
//
// Deploy sketch (custom runtime on `provided.al2`):
//   - a `bootstrap` executable whose body is, in effect, `exec ai-lang run main`
//   - package {bootstrap, the .ai-lang codebase} (zip or container image)
//   - CreateFunction Runtime=provided.al2, Handler unused
// Program A (examples/aws_lambda_demo.ail) then invokes it.

// The business logic: map an event (JSON) to a response (JSON).
def handler(event: String) -> String =
    match json_field(event, "name") {
        Result::Ok(name) => str3("{\"greeting\":\"hello ", name, "\"}"),
        Result::Err(e) => "{\"greeting\":\"hello world\"}"
    }

// The custom-runtime entry point. A deployed worker's `main` is just
// `lambda_serve` wrapping the handler in a closure.
def main() -> Int = lambda_serve(|e: String| handler(e))
